DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain addresses a fundamental tension in political philosophy between
the rights of incumbent residents to remain in place (occupancy rights) and
the claims of outsiders to access territory or neighborhoods. The "occupancy
turn" emerged with Anna Stilz's work on territorial sovereignty (2019),
grounding territorial rights in individuals' occupancy rather than collective
self-determination alone. Huber and Wolkenstein (2018) extended this framework
to gentrification, arguing that residents have occupancy rights to remain in
neighborhoods where their "located life plans" are anchored.

The domain encompasses three interconnected debates: (1) philosophical
foundations of occupancy rights (Stilz, Moore, Mancilla), (2) gentrification
ethics and displacement justice (Lloyd, van Leeuwen, Dawkins, Draper, Jenkins),
and (3) the tension between protection of existing residents and claims of
newcomers. Recent work increasingly recognizes that gentrification threatens
not only through direct displacement but through neighborhood transformation
that disrupts the "background conditions" enabling residents' life plans.

Key recent developments (2020-2025) include: more sophisticated accounts of
what makes displacement wrongful beyond property loss (Lloyd 2023, van Leeuwen
2024); attention to domination and structural injustice in gentrification
(Jenkins 2022, Hoover 2023); and recognition that occupancy rights create
democratic claims over neighborhood governance (Wells 2021, Draper 2022).
A critical gap remains: few theorists directly address the contractualist
stand-off between incumbents and excluded outsiders.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is central to the research project's examination of the
contractualist dilemma in housing justice. The occupancy rights literature
establishes that incumbents have weighty claims to stability and protection
from displacement, grounded in their located life plans. However, the literature
largely fails to address how these occupancy-based claims can be justified to
excluded outsiders who also need access to place to pursue their life plans.
This gap represents precisely the contractualist impasse the research project
aims to illuminate: principles protecting occupancy cannot be justified to the
excluded, yet principles prioritizing access cannot be justified to vulnerable
incumbents facing displacement.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The literature focuses overwhelmingly on incumbent protection, with minimal
attention to access claims of excluded populations. Few papers explicitly
address the trade-off between occupancy and access, or examine how principles
might balance these competing claims. The contractualist framing of this
tension is entirely absent. Additionally, most work focuses on gentrification
in affluent nations, with limited attention to displacement in the Global South
or to climate-induced displacement that raises similar occupancy vs. access
tensions.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis should map two primary positions: (1) occupancy-priority views
that emphasize protection of incumbent residents (Stilz, Huber & Wolkenstein,
Moore), and (2) emerging critiques that identify limitations of pure occupancy
approaches (Mancilla on dynamic occupancy, Lloyd on community goods). The
synthesis should emphasize that while the occupancy literature provides rich
resources for understanding incumbent claims, it systematically neglects the
perspective of excluded outsiders—precisely the blindspot a contractualist
analysis would reveal.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Occupancy Rights Theory: 8 papers - Incumbents have moral rights to remain in
  place where life plans are located (Stilz, Huber & Wolkenstein, Moore, Lloyd)
- Gentrification as Rights Violation: 7 papers - Displacement and transformation
  violate occupancy rights (van Leeuwen, Dawkins, Wells, Draper, Jenkins)
- Access vs. Occupancy Tension: 3 papers - Recognition of competing claims
  (Mancilla, Kim & Walton, Bonotti & Barnhill)
====================================================================
}

